{"title":"Learning-to-Rank at the Speed of Sampling: Plackett-Luce Gradient Estimation With Minimal Computational Complexity","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing stochastic learning-to-rank methods for Plackett–Luce (PL) models (e.g., PL-Rank-1/2, StochasticRank) perform unbiased policy-gradient estimation but their computational cost scales poorly with ranking length K and the number of items D, making long-cutoff optimization impractical.","method":"Introduce PL-Rank-3, an unbiased policy-gradient estimator that computes the same metric-based gradient approximation as PL-Rank-2 while reducing complexity from O(N·D·K) to O(N·(D + K·log D)) for N samples. It samples rankings using Gumbel perturbations and then, per sampled ranking, computes placement reward PR_y,i, risk RI_y,i, and expected direct reward DR_y,i in O(K), reusing these quantities across all D items to eliminate per-item summations over K. The overall cost is thus dominated by the (partial) sorting inherent to sampling, matching the order of fast sorting algorithms."},{"problem":"In practice, training time of LTR algorithms grows sharply with K, limiting scalability without sacrificing performance; a faster method is needed that preserves or improves ranking quality while reducing wall-clock time.","method":"Empirically evaluate PL-Rank-3 on Yahoo! Webscope-Set1, MSLR-Web30k, and Istella across K∈{5,10,25,50,100} and N∈{100,1000}. PL-Rank-3 completes epochs substantially faster and is nearly insensitive to K, consistently achieving the lowest epoch times versus PL-Rank-2 and StochasticRank (e.g., on Istella N=100, increasing K from 5 to 100 adds ~28s for PL-Rank-3 versus +25–49 minutes for baselines). Over 200 minutes of training, PL-Rank-3 attains equal or higher NDCG in most scenarios, despite StochasticRank’s higher sample efficiency, and provides the first direct comparison to StochasticRank by adapting it to Gumbel noise."}]}
